11.body:
Dictionaries are key-value pairs. Values can be assigned and accessed using [] brakets. ss dict_ = {'apples': 10, 'oranges':15}
print(dict_)
print(dict_['apples'])
dict_['apples'] = 20
print(dict_['apples'])
print(dict_.keys())
print(dict_.values()) Output {'apples': 10, 'oranges': 15}
10
20
dict_keys(['apples', 'oranges'])
dict_values([20, 15])

2.body:
Comments are helper text to give better understanding of the code flow. Comments are ignored by interpreter or compiler . Python supports folowing comments # Single line comments Single line comments start with '#' and any text following it till the end of the line is comment # This is example of a single line comment
print("Hello World") # This is another variant of a single line comment Multi line comments Multi line strings have """ or ''' on either end can be used as comments. These are mostly used for documentation of blocks like functions, classes etc. """
This is the example for multi line comment
"""
2.title: Comments

3.body:
Following is the syntax for creating variables. <variable name> = <value> In python we cannot declare variables without assignment. a = 5
print(a)
mystr = "This is a string"
print(mystr) Output 5
This is a string

4.body: Cannot declare variables without assignment. Cannot use Python's keywords as variables. Variables must start with a letter or an unmderscore. Variables may consists of letters, numbers and underscores. Variables cannot have spaces Variables are case sensitive

5.body: Different types of data can be stored in variables. The datatype of a variable is dictated by the value assigned to it at that time of execution. Python has following datatypes Numerical String Python has following collection types Lists Tuples Sets Dictionaries

6.body:
In Python there are three numerical data types. Integer Float Complex int_num = 11
print(type(int_num)) float_num = 3.15
print(type(float_num)) complex_num = 5j
print(type(complex_num)) Output <class 'int'>
<class 'float'>
<class 'complex'>

8.body:
A list is a ordered collection of items. Items can be of any datatype including List Lists are mutable. Once declared the items can be changed, size can be changed. list_ = ['abc', 123, ['a', "String"]] print(list_)
print(list_[0:2])
print(list_[2][0])
list_[0] = 'xyz'
print(list_) Output ['abc', 123, ['a', "String"]]
['abc', 123]
a
['xyz', 123, ['a', "String"]]

9.body:
A tuple is a ordered collection of items. Tuples are immutable. Once declared the items cannot be changed, size cannot be changed. tuple_ = ('abc', 123, ['a', "String"]) print(tuple_)
print(tuple_[0:2])
print(tuple_[2][0])
tuple_[0] = 'xyz'
print(tuple_) Output ('abc', 123, ['a', "String"])
